  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 위로 …… 이루고 : '
    value: 재상(宰相)은 천자를 보좌하여 음양(陰陽)을 섭리함을 직책으로 한다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 왕상(王常)의 자리 : '
    value: 대장군이 된 것을 말한다. 후한(後漢)의 광무제(光武帝)가 왕상(王常)을 대장군으로 삼아서 다른 장수보다 특별한 자리에 앉게 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 곽거병(藿去病)이 …… 것 : '
    value: 곽거병은 서한(西漢) 때의 명장으로 흉노(匈奴)를 쳐서 큰 공을 세웠다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 곽자의(郭子儀)가 …… 것 : '
    value: 곽자의는 당(唐)나라 현종(玄宗) 때의 공신이며 명장이다. 회흘(回紇)이 침입하자 곽자의가 갑주와 창을 버리고 앞으로 나아가 그의 대장 약갈라(藥葛羅)의 손을 잡고 꾸짖으니 감복하여 토번치기를 맹세하였다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 오병(五兵) : '
    value: 극(戟)ㆍ궁(弓) 등의 다섯 가지 무기를 말하는데, 《주례(周禮)》에, “하관(夏官)이 오병(五兵)을 맡는다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 남금(南金) : '
    value: 형주(荊州)와 양주(楊州)에서 나는 질이 좋은 금을 말한다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 동전(東箭) : '
    value: 중국의 동남방 회계(會稽)에서 나는 죽전(竹箭)이 가장 좋다고 한다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 어부(魚符) : '
    value: 나무나 구리로 고기 모양처럼 만들어서 수령(守令)들이 가지는 병부(兵符)이다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 웅식(熊軾) : '
    value: 수레에 곰을 그린 것인데, 자사(刺史)가 타는 소레이다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 기린의 뿔 : '
    value: 배우는 자는 쇠털같이 많은데 성공하는 자는 기린뿔같이 적다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 공분(孔奮) : '
    value: 동한(東漢)광무제(光武帝) 때의 사람으로, 효도하고 청렴하기로 이름났다.
  - key: '[주-D012] 문요(文饒) : '
    value: 유관(劉寬)의 자(字). 동한(東漢)환제(桓帝) 때의 사람으로 온화하고 인자하여 용서함이 많았다.
  - key: '[주-D013] 양주(陽朱) : '
    value: 극도의 이기주의자. 털을 하나 뽑아서 천하의 이가 되어도 하지 않았다.
  - key: '[주-D014] 묵적(墨翟) : '
    value: 겸해(兼愛)주의자로서 이마부터 발꿈치까지 같아도 천하의 이(利)가 된다면 하는 사상이다.
  - key: '[주-D015] 한유(韓愈) : '
    value: 당나라 때의 대문호. 불교를 원도(原道)라는 문(文)을 지어 노(老)ㆍ불(佛)을 배척하였다.
  - key: '[주-D016] 인필(麟筆) : '
    value: 사필(史筆)을 말함. 공자가 ‘기린을 얻은 데에서 붓을 놓았다[絶筆於獲麟].’ 한 데서 나온 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D017] 황종(黃鐘) : '
    value: 12율(律)의 처음인데 율관(律管)의 표준이 된다.
  - key: '[주-D018] 채관(豸冠) : '
    value: 해채(獬豸)는 신양(神羊)인데, 능히 곡직(曲直)을 분별한다. 그러므로 집법자(執法者)의 관(冠)을 채관(豸冠)이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D019] 북쪽에서는 …… 가졌는데 : '
    value: 한 무제(漢武帝)가 지방(地方)에 어사(御使)를 보낼 때 비단옷을 입게 하고 도끼를 주어서 생살(生殺)의 권한을 맡겼다.
  - key: '[주-D020] 비단 …… 칼 : '
    value: 춘추(春秋) 시대에 자산(子産)이 말하기를, “아름다운 비단을 가지고 옷을 마련하는 데는 서투른 사람에게 시험삼아 맡기면 비단을 버릴 염려가 있는 것처럼, 고을을 맡겨서 백성을 다스리는 데는 서투른 사람에게 시험삼아 함부로 맡겨서는 안 된다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D021] 극림(棘林) : '
    value: 가시나무 숲으로, 《예기》를 보면 대사구(大司寇)가 극목(棘木) 밑에서 옥사(獄事)를 청단(聽斷)하였으므로 극림(棘林)에는 밤에 우는 귀신이 많다 하였다. 《예기(禮記)》
  - key: '[주-D022] 잣나무 …… 있었다 : '
    value: 어사부(御史府) 가운데에 잣나무가 늘어서 있는데, 항상 까마귀 수천 마리가 그 위에 깃들어서 새벽에 날아갔다가 저물면 돌아왔다.
  - key: '[주-D023] 내상(內相) : '
    value: 당(唐)나라 육지(陸贄)가 한림학사(翰林學士)로서 임금의 측근에서 기밀(機密)에 참예하니, 당시 사람들이 그를 내상(內相)이라 불렀다.
  - key: '[주-D024] 준조(樽爼) : '
    value: 연회(宴會)에 차리는 술병과 고기 담은 도마를 말하는데, 여기서는 외적에 대하여 연회석상에서 담판을 하여 침략을 방지한다는 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D025] 금초(金貂) : '
    value: 한(漢)나라의 시중(侍中)중상시(中常侍)가 황금당(黃金璫)에 매미를 붙이고 초미(貂尾)로 관식(冠飾)하였다. 김일제(金日磾)의 집이 7대로 금초였다.
  - key: '[주-D026] 긴 바람을 …… 가졌고 : '
    value: 남북조 때에 종각(宗慤)이 어릴 적에 그의 숙부가 장래의 뜻을 물으니 답하기를, “긴 바람을 타고 만리의 물결을 헤쳐가기가 소원입니다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D027] 밝은 …… 나타내었다 : '
    value: 당나라 양염(楊炎)이 벼슬하기 전에, 꿈에 높은 산에 올라 해가 가까이 있는 것을 보고 손을 들어 받들었다고 했더니, 해몽하는 이가 말하기를, “이것은 장차 정승이 되어 임금을 보좌할 상서로운 꿈이다.” 하였는데, 후일에 과연 맞았다.
  - key: '[주-D028] 화곤(華袞) : '
    value: 곤룡포로, 공자가 《춘추(春秋)》를 지어 인물을 표창하고 폄하하였는데, “한 마디의 표창은 빛나는 곤룡포보다 영화스럽고, 한 마디의 폄한 것은 도끼보다 무섭다.” 하였다.
  - key: '[주-D029] 사지(四知)와 삼이(三異) : '
    value: 사지는 한나라 양진(楊震)이 뇌물을 받고서는 하늘이 알고 땅이 알고 네가 알고 내가 안다고 하면서 물리친 고사를 말한다. 삼이는 노공(魯恭)이 중모령(中牟令)이 되었을 때에 벌레가 지경을 범하지 않고, 덕화가 새와 짐승에 미치고, 수자(竪子)가 인(仁)이 있었던 것을 말한다.
english:
  title: Proclamation of Appointment
  author: Lee Baek-soon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To the Ministry below: The five stars align like pearls—Wood becomes civil virtue, Metal becomes martial prowess. The four peaks stand as sentinels—Mount Tai to the east, Mount Hua to the west. When one ascends to perfect Heaven's work and accomplishes the harmony of all things, when one follows Earth's course to illuminate the great tapestry of governance, should not such service be crowned with imperial favor? Thus we proclaim to the enlightened court.

    Officer Kim Jiruryeo possesses the keen gaze of a swallow, the singular bearing of a dragon's whisker. His archery reaches sublime mastery, swift as thunder's voice. His battle tactics commune with spirits, quick as lightning's strike. Meeting the times as a man of heroic mettle, advancing with vigor in affairs of state, he soared through the ranks of the palace guard and rose among the lesser generals. His silk robes grew wet with the dew of the Forbidden Forest, entering the nine-tiered palace countless times. His golden armor gathered frost on distant borders, patrolling ten thousand li again and again. He sat in the seat of a great commander and ascended to the rank of Han Xin. When the Khitans breached our lands and the Jurchen crossed our boundaries, he became the deputy in campaigns and held sole command of divided domains. Receiving orders, he forgot his home and gave his body to the nation. At first he swept through battles like Huo Qubing at Yanzhishi; at last he removed his helmet to meet envoys like Guo Ziyi before the Uighurs. Thus the two commanders became as intimate friends, and the two nations relied upon his peace.

    Outwardly he became the Great Wall, inwardly he bore up the great house. Swift was his promotion to a position near the throne, sudden his rise to the heights of office. The pillar of five dynasties, the beam of one kingdom—having accomplished such lasting peace within and without, surely he deserves rare imperial grace. We hereby appoint him Grand General commanding the five weapons, conferring also the powers of strategist; as Minister of the Center controlling all officials, elevating him to the rank of Prime Minister, making him the chief administrator of the imperial bureaus. Let him be specially appointed Guardian General of the Center, Attendant Minister of the Chancellery, and Prime Minister, with jurisdiction over the Ministry of War. All else remains unchanged.

    Officer Choi Jungbun—his substance gleams like southern gold, his talents surpass eastern arrows. His discernment shines bright as heaven's torch held high, his integrity flows pure as moonlight trapped in ice. Through the examination for the virtuous and capable, he plucked the whiskers of the dragon and easily grasped office. Ascending twice to the Remonstrance Bureau, he opened his heart to offer pearls of wisdom; long stationed in the Edict Garden, he opened his mouth to spill forth embroidered words. Abundant in honors and crucial posts, he weathered grave difficulties. Three times wearing the fish-tablet of authority, spring's warmth blessed the people's skin; twice resting upon the official's chariot, autumn frost chilled the officials' hearts.

    He managed the treasury of maps and books, wielded authority over salt and iron. As Rector of the Academy, he taught students who all became like the rare horns of the unicorn; as Supervisor of Selections, he chose scholars who all obtained the liver of the dragon. When presenting memorials, he drew near the imperial brazier's fragrance; when signing decrees, he gazed upon the celestial countenance. His seal bore the rank of Hanlin Scholar; his authority encompassed that of the Chief Censor. Through five reigns he served, his reputation high among a hundred officials. Though placed in the fat and marrow of power, he never soiled his integrity—exceeding Kong Fen's purity. Though reaching the peak of minister, he never ceased his reading—matching Wen Rao's elegance.

    Moreover, grieving that younger scholars fell into heterodoxy, he caused all to study the Six Classics, drawing them near to the ways of antiquity. This was as when Yang Zhu and Mo Di blocked the sage's path, and Mencius rebuked and cleared it; as when the Buddha and Laozi damaged the great Dike, and Han Yu pressed and rebuilt it. He became the lodestone for the downward flood, the primordial turtle for established virtue. We therefore command that his silver insignia be changed to gold; let him bathe in the Phoenixpool of honors while overseeing the brush of the unicorn in historical compilation. Let him be specially appointed Golden Purple Grandee of the Third Rank, Director of State History. All else remains unchanged.

    Officer Choi Jongjun—his tone accords with the Yellow Bell pitch, his conduct equals white jade. His pure bearing shines forth in the world like snow-capped mountains soaring into emptiness, his bracing spirit penetrates hearts like an ice-gorge washing away summer's heat. Young, he inherited through family rank and early assumed noble position. In the Eastern Palace he wore the rhinoceros belt; transferred to the secret inspection, he donned the pheasant crown. To the north he bore the embroidered robe and axe of inspection, formidable and commanding wind itself; to the south he wielded the knife of silk-dyed judgment, expansive and leaving room for mercy.

    He endured all the turmoil of the Ministry of Works, traversed the complexities of the Ministries of Personnel and War. Three times entering the Court of Punishments, no ghostly wails echoed through the thorn-grove at night; four times ascending to the Censorate, dawn-returning ravens still nested in the cypress trees. He managed the protocols of the Gate of Heaven, commanded the armies of the Palace Guard. Speaking commands at the jade steps, advancing to positions in the inner circle, he became the private counselor of the Son of Heaven, the inner minister of the imperial court.

    When the northern barbarians crept like thieves and southern tribes prowled like wolves, he commanded at the feast-table with the diplomacy of Yan Zi, calculated victory in the war-tent surpassing Zhang Liang. The people all looked up to him, and we cherished his virtue greatly. Therefore we transfer him to the palace ministries and commission him to oversee personnel selection. Let him be specially appointed Golden Purple Grandee, Director of the Ministry of Personnel, Censor of the Gate Secretariat. All else remains unchanged.

    Officer Kim Junggui—his house stems from golden marten lineage, his name resounds like a jade tiger's roar. Riding the long wind, he breaks through great waves—from youth possessed of grand designs; bearing aloft the bright sun, he ascends the high mountain—early manifesting auspicious omens. In his youth he entered the inner guard; long he served in the celestial court. Drawing the deer-chariot once, he proclaimed the king's transformation; raising the falcon-banner twice, he inspected the people's customs. One word of praise—his integrity like clear ice—outweighs robes of brocade.

    Soon he became the commander's claw and fang, swiftly the minister's mouth and tongue. His wise counsels accord with the admonitions of Jun Chen; his noble bearing matches Zhong Shanfu's presence at court. In all his comings and goings, in danger and ease alike, his integrity remained steadfast. Northward he entered the land of ten thousand deaths and one survival to resist the Khitans; westward he defended the old capital and earned the fame of Four Knowledges and Three Wonders. Like fine jade hardened further in fire, like faithful pine more luxuriant under snow.

    We therefore summoned him back to the capital and renewed his appointments. Let his seal bear the rank of Censor of the Gate Ministry; let him participate in the inner councilor's duties, becoming foremost among generals and master of the realm's treasuries. Let him be specially appointed Golden Purple Grandee, Director of the Gate Ministry, Minister of Personnel, Prime Minister of the Left, and Commissioner of the Three Departments.

    Alas! I liken myself to gold and take you as my skilled craftsman. You become my rudder that I may cross the mighty river. Thus serving and fulfilling one another, we arrive together at the Way.
  footnotes:
    - Han Xin was a celebrated general of the Han Dynasty, elevated to the highest military rank by Emperor Guangwu of the Later Han.
    - Huo Qubing was a renowned Western Han general who achieved great victories against the Xiongnu.
    - Guo Ziyi was a celebrated Tang Dynasty general and statesman who famously met with Uighur leaders, establishing peace through diplomatic mastery.
    - The fish-tablet (yu fu) was an insignia of office given to provincial governors, conferring authority over military forces.
    - Kong Fen was known in the Eastern Han for his purity and filial devotion; Wen Rao (Liu Kuan) for his gentle scholarship and virtue.
    - Yang Zhu represented extreme egoism; Mo Di advocated universal love—both philosophies opposed the Sage's teachings, as Mencius refuted them.
    - Han Yu, the great Tang literatus, combated Buddhist and Daoist influence through his essay 'On the Origin of the Way.'
    - The unicorn's horn symbolizes rarity of achievement; the dragon's liver represents supreme excellence in government.
    - The Yellow Bell is the first and fundamental pitch in the ancient system of musical tones.
    - The pheasant crown was worn by officials responsible for law and justice.
    - The Four Knowledges refers to Yang Zhen's refusal of bribes, saying heaven knows, earth knows, you know, and I know. The Three Wonders refers to Lu Gong's benevolent governance affecting all creatures.
